leads you to play it

1310
00:44:17,040 --> 00:44:19,120
with the execution of its mechanics.

1311
00:44:19,120 --> 00:44:20,960
When a game kills you very easily,

1312
00:44:20,960 --> 00:44:22,240
tells you to prepare to die,

1313
00:44:22,240 --> 00:44:23,200
and hands you a shield,

1314
00:44:23,200 --> 00:44:24,400
and teaches you how to use it,

1315
00:44:24,400 --> 00:44:25,520
you're taught specific rules

1316
00:44:25,520 --> 00:44:26,480
about that game's world

1317
00:44:26,480 --> 00:44:27,520
and it sticks with you.

1318
00:44:27,520 --> 00:44:28,880
The rest of the game experience

1319
00:44:28,880 --> 00:44:29,920
could have been better served

1320
00:44:29,920 --> 00:44:31,520
by a different early approach,

1321
00:44:31,520 --> 00:44:33,360
but you've been quite definitively taught

1322
00:44:33,360 --> 00:44:34,480
a specific one

1323
00:44:34,480 --> 00:44:35,600
and it'll probably be a struggle

1324
00:44:35,600 --> 00:44:36,560
to unlearn it.

1325
00:44:36,560 --> 00:44:37,760
I brought this up in the video

1326
00:44:37,760 --> 00:44:39,040
to make the point that Bloodborne

1327
00:44:39,040 --> 00:44:40,640
quite deftly pushes the player

1328
00:44:40,640 --> 00:44:42,320
into a more frenetic direction

1329
00:44:42,320 --> 00:44:43,600
with a few subtle changes

1330
00:44:43,600 --> 00:44:44,720
to its base mechanics

1331
00:44:44,720 --> 00:44:46,960
and much wider reaching executions

1332
00:44:46,960 --> 00:44:48,240
of those mechanics.

1333
00:44:48,240 --> 00:44:50,400
There is still one or maybe two

1334
00:44:50,400 --> 00:44:51,360
shields in the game,

1335
00:44:51,360 --> 00:44:53,600
but you don't find them for so long

1336
00:44:53,600 --> 00:44:55,440
that you learned not to use them.

1337
00:44:55,440 --> 00:44:57,040
They exist almost to show you

1338
00:44:57,040 --> 00:44:59,200
that you never really needed them.

1339
00:44:59,200 --> 00:45:01,440
The shield engendered passivity.

1340
00:45:01,440 --> 00:45:03,520
That wording's actually kind of genius.

1341
00:45:03,520 --> 00:45:05,200
The game's own item description

1342
00:45:05,200 --> 00:45:07,440
directly blames shields themselves,

1343
00:45:07,440 --> 00:45:09,040
not players for not realizing

1344
00:45:09,040 --> 00:45:10,560
how they're supposed to use them.

1345
00:45:10,560 --> 00:45:12,400
I think that's really clever

1346
00:45:12,400 --> 00:45:13,760
and also an honest admission

1347
00:45:13,760 --> 00:45:14,960
that they kind of messed up

1348
00:45:14,960 --> 00:45:16,160
in Dark Souls 1.

1349
00:45:16,160 --> 00:45:17,840
Some folks disagreed with my comments

1350
00:45:17,840 --> 00:45:18,720
that playing with a shield

1351
00:45:18,720 --> 00:45:20,080
was an inherently wrong,

1352
00:45:20,080 --> 00:45:21,600
slow, overly defensive,

1353
00:45:21,600 --> 00:45:22,720
or boring way to play,

1354
00:45:22,720 --> 00:45:24,240
and I do have to stress

1355
00:45:24,240 --> 00:45:25,600
that's just my opinion.

1356
00:45:25,600 --> 00:45:27,440
You can play the games however you want.

1357
00:45:27,440 --> 00:45:28,720
I'm just describing how the game

1358
00:45:28,720 --> 00:45:30,480
is most fun in my opinion

1359
00:45:30,480 --> 00:45:31,680
and the ways I think the game

1360
00:45:31,680 --> 00:45:32,960
leads people to play it

1361
00:45:32,960 --> 00:45:34,000
in those more fun ways

1362
00:45:34,000 --> 00:45:35,040
than the previous ones.

1363
00:45:35,040 --> 00:45:36,480
While Bloodborne is undisputedly

1364
00:45:36,480 --> 00:45:37,520
the master of this,

1365
00:45:37,520 --> 00:45:38,560
Dark Souls 2 does a lot

1366
00:45:38,560 --> 00:45:39,680
of really great things

1367
00:45:39,680 --> 00:45:41,120
with play conditioning also,

1368
00:45:41,120 --> 00:45:42,480
things that other critics dismiss

1369
00:45:42,480 --> 00:45:43,440
as minor tweaks

1370
00:45:43,440 --> 00:45:44,960
or just don't talk about at all.

1371
00:45:44,960 --> 00:45:45,920
In the Bloodborne video,

1372
00:45:45,920 --> 00:45:47,360
my central example was the shield,

1373
00:45:47,360 --> 00:45:48,960
and we might as well start there too

1374
00:45:48,960 --> 00:45:49,760
because people don't

1375
00:45:49,760 --> 00:45:50,720
fucking mention this.

1376
00:45:50,720 --> 00:45:52,160
Dark Souls 2 has shields.

1377
00:45:52,160 --> 00:45:53,200
It has plenty of them,

1378
00:45:53,200 --> 00:45:54,080
and they're fine.

1379
00:45:54,080 --> 00:45:54,720
They work well,

1380
00:45:54,720 --> 00:45:56,400
and you can get some very defend-y ones

1381
00:45:56,400 --> 00:45:57,600
that do all the stuff you need,

1382
00:45:57,600 --> 00:45:58,640
and you can buff them

1383
00:45:58,640 --> 00:46:00,080
lots of different ways too,

1384
00:46:00,080 --> 00:46:01,520
but here's the thing.

1385
00:46:01,520 --> 00:46:03,360
Only one class

1386
00:46:03,360 --> 00:46:05,360
starts with a shield at all

1387
00:46:05,360 --> 00:46:06,880
in Dark Souls 2.

1388
00:46:06,880 --> 00:46:09,040
In fact, that class, the warrior,

1389
00:46:09,040 --> 00:46:11,520
begins life with a broken sword.

1390
00:46:11,520 --> 00:46:12,320
Every other character

1391
00:46:12,320 --> 00:46:13,360
starts with some semblance

1392
00:46:13,360 --> 00:46:14,560
of a fighting setup.

1393
00:46:14,560 --> 00:46:16,080
The knight has a broadsword,

1394
00:46:16,080 --> 00:46:18,160
the swordsman has two plus one swords,

1395
00:46:18,160 --> 00:46:20,000
the bandit has an axe and a bow,

1396
00:46:20,000 --> 00:46:20,800
and so on.

1397
00:46:20,800 --> 00:46:22,080
Starting with a shield

1398
00:46:22,080 --> 00:46:23,440
handicaps you in many ways

1399
00:46:23,440 --> 00:46:24,400
at the start of this game.

1400
00:46:24,400 --> 00:46:26,320
It forces you to use ingenuity

1401
00:46:26,320 --> 00:46:27,360
to get access to a weapon

1402
00:46:27,360 --> 00:46:28,400
that's more viable.

1403
00:46:28,400 --> 00:46:30,400
It's not even that great a shield.

1404
00:46:30,400 --> 00:46:32,000
Other classes having no shield

1405
00:46:32,000 --> 00:46:34,000
are forced to use dodging or parrying

1406
00:46:34,000 --> 00:46:35,920
or make good use of what they're given.

1407
00:46:35,920 --> 00:46:38,240
This is a tiny, tiny, simple change

1408
00:46:38,240 --> 00:46:40,000
to just starting loadouts,

1409
00:46:40,000 --> 00:46:42,240
but it's fantastic design.

1410
00:46:42,400 --> 00:46:43,600
It alters the shape

1411
00:46:43,600 --> 00:46:45,680
of the entire game experience.

1412
00:46:45,680 --> 00:46:47,920
You're expected, told even,

1413
00:46:47,920 --> 00:46:48,960
to make use of the engine

1414
00:46:48,960 --> 00:46:50,000
in a vastly different way

1415
00:46:50,000 --> 00:46:50,960
from how you're led to think

1416
00:46:50,960 --> 00:46:52,800
you're supposed to play the first game.

1417
00:46:52,800 --> 00:46:54,240
Shields you acquire early on

1418
00:46:54,240 --> 00:46:56,000
don't even block 100% of damage,

1419
00:46:56,000 --> 00:46:57,360
and you don't have much life,

1420
00:46:57,360 --> 00:46:59,520
so blocking is treated as a last resort

1421
00:46:59,520 --> 00:47:00,560
for if you really don't know

1422
00:47:00,560 --> 00:47:02,080
what else to do about an attack

1423
00:47:02,080 --> 00:47:03,760
or haven't learned its timing yet.

1424
00:47:03,760 --> 00:47:05,600
Dark Souls 2 is the first game in the series

1425
00:47:05,600 --> 00:47:06,800
where you started getting players

1426
00:47:06,800 --> 00:47:08,400
who were more casually walking around

1427
00:47:08,400 --> 00:47:09,440
without a shield at all,

1428
00:47:09,440 --> 00:47:10,640
preferring two-handing

1429
00:47:10,640 --> 00:47:12,080
or the new power stance

1430
00:47:12,080 --> 00:47:13,840
added for dual-wielding characters.

1431
00:47:13,840 --> 00:47:15,040
By the time you reach shields

1432
00:47:15,040 --> 00:47:16,400
that actually block lots of damage

1433
00:47:16,400 --> 00:47:18,400
the way early shields did in the first game,

1434
00:47:18,400 --> 00:47:19,680
you've employed a level of skill

1435
00:47:19,680 --> 00:47:21,120
getting to them that means using them

1436
00:47:21,120 --> 00:47:22,480
would be a waste of a good hand

1437
00:47:22,480 --> 00:47:24,240
you could be keeping another weapon in

1438
00:47:24,240 --> 00:47:25,120
or some magic.

1439
00:47:25,120 --> 00:47:26,240
Dodging like this would have seemed

1440
00:47:26,240 --> 00:47:28,400
like a needless, risky waste of time

1441
00:47:28,400 --> 00:47:30,080
to the old me if I had a shield

1442
00:47:30,080 --> 00:47:32,160
and could block the damage perfectly well,

1443
00:47:32,160 --> 00:47:33,680
but it would have been so slow.

1444
00:47:33,680 --> 00:47:35,120
You don't need Dark Souls 2

1445
00:47:35,120 --> 00:47:36,560
to teach you to play this way, obviously.

1446
00:47:36,560 --> 00:47:37,600
You can figure it out

1447
00:47:37,600 --> 00:47:38,720
if you do a lot of practicing

1448
00:47:38,720 --> 00:47:40,080
or look up a lot of YouTube videos

1449
00:47:40,080 --> 00:47:41,680
or do PvP or whatever,

1450
00:47:41,680 --> 00:47:43,520
but being forced to play that way

1451
00:47:43,520 --> 00:47:44,480
by the game

1452
00:47:44,480 --> 00:47:46,560
makes you learn it so much faster.

1453
00:47:46,560 --> 00:47:48,240
Other touches can be seen here, too,

1454
00:47:48,240 --> 00:47:49,200
like parrying.

1455
00:47:49,200 --> 00:47:50,880
In Dark Souls 1, parrying offered

1456
00:47:50,880 --> 00:47:52,480
a brief, clumsy moment

1457
00:47:52,480 --> 00:47:53,680
to get in a riposte.

1458
00:47:53,680 --> 00:47:55,360
Oh, and you can't even do a riposte

1459
00:47:55,360 --> 00:47:57,520
if you're two-handing in Dark Souls 1.

1460
00:47:57,520 --> 00:48:00,000
Thanks, fuckers.

1461
00:48:00,000 --> 00:48:01,840
The sound effect was satisfying

1462
00:48:01,840 --> 00:48:02,880
but hard to make out

1463
00:48:02,880 --> 00:48:04,400
if anything else was happening.

1464
00:48:04,400 --> 00:48:06,400
The window to respond was short

1465
00:48:06,400 --> 00:48:07,680
and the animations that played

1466
00:48:07,680 --> 00:48:08,720
where enemies were parried

1467
00:48:08,720 --> 00:48:11,040
were often really short and vague.

1468
00:48:11,040 --> 00:48:12,720
I didn't parry a lot in Dark Souls 1

1469
00:48:12,720 --> 00:48:14,480
because, frankly, I didn't trust the game

1470
00:48:14,480 --> 00:48:16,240
enough to let me capitalize on it.

1471
00:48:16,240 --> 00:48:18,160
In Dark Souls 2, parrying triggers

1472
00:48:18,160 --> 00:48:19,920
a loud, ultra-cool sound.

1473
00:48:22,720 --> 00:48:24,880
The enemies fall down in a protracted

1474
00:48:24,880 --> 00:48:27,120
dear-god-my-entire-world-is-ending

1475
00:48:27,120 --> 00:48:29,280
animation and stay there for ages

1476
00:48:29,280 --> 00:48:31,040
while they wait for you to capitalize.

1477
00:48:31,040 --> 00:48:33,440
This is, in a word, encouraging.

1478
00:48:33,440 --> 00:48:35,440
You feel like you've made a decisive move

1479
00:48:35,440 --> 00:48:37,440
and might even have already won.

1480
00:48:37,440 --> 00:48:38,720
You feel rewarded for learning

1481
00:48:38,720 --> 00:48:40,000
how an enemy attacks.

1482
00:48:40,000 --> 00:48:41,680
It's obvious you've pulled it off

1483
00:48:41,680 --> 00:48:43,280
and you have plenty of time to react

1484
00:48:43,280 --> 00:48:44,640
to knowing you've done it.

1485
00:48:44,640 --> 00:48:46,080
I felt, like I said,

1486
00:48:46,080 --> 00:48:48,240
encouraged to keep parrying.

1487
00:48:48,240 --> 00:48:49,200
Instead of abandoning it

1488
00:48:49,200 --> 00:48:50,080
after the early levels,

1489
00:48:50,080 --> 00:48:51,120
I only really using it

1490
00:48:51,120 --> 00:48:52,720
on heavily choreographed enemies

1491
00:48:52,720 --> 00:48:53,840
like I did in 1.

1492
00:48:53,840 --> 00:48:55,440
Parrying really only came into its own

1493
00:48:55,440 --> 00:48:57,040
in Bloodborne which handed you a weapon

1494
00:48:57,040 --> 00:48:58,560
specifically for doing it

1495
00:48:58,560 --> 00:49:00,960
and made even monstrous enemies parryable

1496
00:49:00,960 --> 00:49:02,160
but this represents a step

1497
00:49:02,160 --> 00:49:03,440
in the right direction.

1498
00:49:03,440 --> 00:49:05,280
I realized, playing Dark Souls 2,

1499
00:49:05,280 --> 00:49:07,040
that the reason it seemed too hard

1500
00:49:07,040 --> 00:49:08,640
to get to the level of skill

1501
00:49:08,640 --> 00:49:09,920
other people were displaying

1502
00:49:09,920 --> 00:49:11,360
was because getting there required

1503
00:49:11,360 --> 00:49:13,600
lots of time investment and practice

1504
00:49:13,600 --> 00:49:14,640
to get around the fact

1505
00:49:14,640 --> 00:49:16,720
the game itself did a pretty bad job

1506
00:49:16,720 --> 00:49:18,240
of getting you there by itself.

1507
00:49:18,240 --> 00:49:18,880
The phrase,

1508
00:49:18,880 --> 00:49:20,720
"'Get good' has been around for ages

1509
00:49:20,720 --> 00:49:22,480
but was massively popularized

1510
00:49:22,480 --> 00:49:23,680
in the Souls community

1511
00:49:23,680 --> 00:49:25,280
and this is because the gulf of skill

1512
00:49:25,280 --> 00:49:26,800
is so wide between new

1513
00:49:26,800 --> 00:49:28,080
and experienced players

1514
00:49:28,080 --> 00:49:29,360
that it's almost impossible

1515
00:49:29,360 --> 00:49:31,200
to help someone get on their level,

1516
00:49:31,200 --> 00:49:32,960
the only advice being, basically,

1517
00:49:32,960 --> 00:49:34,960
to keep playing until they become good

1518
00:49:34,960 --> 00:49:35,760
at the game.

1519
00:49:35,760 --> 00:49:36,960
No matter how you look at it,

1520
00:49:36,960 --> 00:49:38,640
the fact the community has trouble

1521
00:49:38,640 --> 00:49:40,400
introducing the game it's built around

1522
00:49:40,400 --> 00:49:41,760
to new players

1523
00:49:41,760 --> 00:49:43,520
constitutes something of a problem

1524
00:49:43,520 --> 00:49:45,440
and this is a problem I feel Dark Souls 2

1525
00:49:45,440 --> 00:49:47,200
solves with some very careful changes

1526
00:49:47,200 --> 00:49:48,000
in its design.

1527
00:49:48,000 --> 00:49:49,040
I said before that I thought

1528
00:49:49,040 --> 00:49:50,320
Dark Souls was incredible

1529
00:49:50,320 --> 00:49:52,240
but I owe that to DS2

1530
00:49:52,240 --> 00:49:54,640
showing me the way to appreciate it properly

1531
00:49:54,640 --> 00:49:55,680
and the way to approach it

1532
00:49:55,680 --> 00:49:57,520
in a way that was actually really fun.

1533
00:49:58,080 --> 00:49:59,520
The blueprint for Bloodborne,

1534
00:49:59,520 --> 00:50:01,120
the blood print, if you will,

1535
00:50:01,120 --> 00:50:02,880
of a lot of creative decisions,

1536
00:50:02,880 --> 00:50:04,400
lies in Dark Souls 2.

1537
00:50:04,400 --> 00:50:06,240
I'm unsure if it directly inspired

1538
00:50:06,240 --> 00:50:08,000
the attitudes to shields and healing

1539
00:50:08,000 --> 00:50:09,680
and level design and so on in Bloodborne

1540
00:50:09,680 --> 00:50:10,960
but even if it didn't,

1541
00:50:10,960 --> 00:50:12,720
the way Bloodborne seemingly builds

1542
00:50:12,720 --> 00:50:13,760
on these ideas for me

1543
00:50:13,760 --> 00:50:16,240
shows that 2 was a step in the right direction

1544
00:50:16,240 --> 00:50:18,880
even if it didn't get everything right.

1545
00:50:28,880 --> 00:50:31,120
Dark Souls 1 is, on a technical level,

1546
00:50:31,120 --> 00:50:32,480
interesting and complex.

1547
00:50:32,480 --> 00:50:33,920
The opening cinematic explains

1548
00:50:33,920 --> 00:50:35,680
the setup of the world of the story.

1549
00:50:35,680 --> 00:50:38,000
Gwyn and Co. mess up the ancient dragons,

1550
00:50:38,000 --> 00:50:40,400
build a society using the power of the soul,

1551
00:50:40,400 --> 00:50:42,560
and people start becoming undead and going mad

1552
00:50:42,560 --> 00:50:44,080
and the empire eventually collapses

1553
00:50:44,080 --> 00:50:45,280
when the flames start to go out

1554
00:50:45,280 --> 00:50:47,040
and Gwyn fucks up trying to fix it.

1555
00:50:47,040 --> 00:50:48,320
But what the player actually does

1556
00:50:48,320 --> 00:50:50,240
is run around a mostly empty world

1557
00:50:50,240 --> 00:50:51,360
killing the people who remain

1558
00:50:51,360 --> 00:50:52,880
so they can open a big door.

1559
00:50:52,880 --> 00:50:54,720
There isn't much actual interaction

1560
00:50:54,720 --> 00:50:56,080
with this story.

1561
00:50:56,080 --> 00:50:57,520
The stuff about everlasting dragons

1562
00:50:57,520 --> 00:50:58,480
and a war to kill them all

1563
00:50:58,480 --> 00:50:59,920
doesn't really have much of an impact

1564
00:50:59,920 --> 00:51:00,960
on the story of the player

1565
00:51:00,960 --> 00:51:02,240
killing the people who killed them

1566
00:51:02,240 --> 00:51:03,360
and nicking their souls.

1567
00:51:03,360 --> 00:51:05,600
What the first game excels at is lore.

1568
00:51:05,600 --> 00:51:07,440
In the sense that through item descriptions

1569
00:51:07,440 --> 00:51:08,400
and chance encounters

1570
00:51:08,400 --> 00:51:09,840
with the people who remain in the world

1571
00:51:09,840 --> 00:51:11,280
and are safe to talk to,

1572
00:51:11,280 --> 00:51:13,840
you can learn little tidbits about them as people.

1573
00:51:13,840 --> 00:51:15,040
You can run into a character,

1574
00:51:15,040 --> 00:51:16,480
have a brief conversation,

1575
00:51:16,480 --> 00:51:18,480
and be sure that if you pay attention to the world

1576
00:51:18,480 --> 00:51:20,480
and objects related to them or their people,

1577
00:51:20,480 --> 00:51:22,640
you'll learn something about them and their culture.

1578
00:51:22,640 --> 00:51:24,320
The closest you get to a story

1579
00:51:24,320 --> 00:51:26,240
is a guy saying ring some bells.

1580
00:51:26,240 --> 00:51:28,320
There's an old saying in my family.

1581
00:51:28,320 --> 00:51:29,840
Fuck your family.

1582
00:51:29,840 --> 00:51:31,200
This is the reason for the whole mission.

1583
00:51:31,200 --> 00:51:32,400
Like, you meet this guy who's like,

1584
00:51:32,400 --> 00:51:35,200
you know, my family have this fucked up stupid belief.

1585
00:51:35,200 --> 00:51:37,040
Or another guy saying ring some bells.

1586
00:51:37,040 --> 00:51:39,040
Or a serpent saying, hey, Gwyn was cool.

1587
00:51:39,040 --> 00:51:40,080
Kill his friends.

1588
00:51:40,080 --> 00:51:41,680
Or a different serpent saying,

1589
00:51:41,680 --> 00:51:43,040
Gwyn wasn't cool at all.

1590
00:51:43,040 --> 00:51:44,320
He was really rude.

1591
00:51:44,320 --> 00:51:45,360
Kill his friends.

1592
00:51:45,360 --> 00:51:47,040
The fun of the game comes from figuring out

1593
00:51:47,040 --> 00:51:49,360
a complete picture of what you can find,

1594
00:51:49,360 --> 00:51:51,280
but there isn't really a narrative

1595
00:51:51,280 --> 00:51:52,720
happening for most of it.

1596
00:51:52,720 --> 00:51:54,400
The player isn't really given a chance

1597
00:51:54,400 --> 00:51:57,040
to interact with the important events in this world.

1598
00:51:57,040 --> 00:51:58,320
They're just picking up the pieces

1599
00:51:58,320 --> 00:51:59,920
of stuff that already happened.

1600
00:51:59,920 --> 00:52:01,600
In comparison, to me,

1601
00:52:01,600 --> 00:52:04,240
Dark Souls 2 does something really interesting.

1602
00:52:04,240 --> 00:52:06,640
You get a cool metaphorical sequence in the opening

1603
00:52:06,640 --> 00:52:09,360
where a Darkseid-branded character's family

1604
00:52:09,360 --> 00:52:11,520
melts away under the weight of the curse

1605
00:52:11,520 --> 00:52:14,080
making you live so long you forget everything.

1606
00:52:14,080 --> 00:52:16,080
Already we're given our first proper theme,

1607
00:52:16,080 --> 00:52:19,040
and it works on both the personal and world level

1608
00:52:19,040 --> 00:52:21,680
in that the world is making less and less sense

1609
00:52:21,680 --> 00:52:23,360
because things are falling away,

1610
00:52:23,360 --> 00:52:25,440
which, by the way, coincides really well

1611
00:52:25,440 --> 00:52:27,440
with the fact the world design is like that.

1612
00:52:27,440 --> 00:52:28,880
The story itself, to start with,

1613
00:52:28,880 --> 00:52:31,520
is self-consciously a rehash of the previous game.

1614
00:52:31,520 --> 00:52:34,080
The Emerald Herald tells you you need to face the king,

1615
00:52:34,080 --> 00:52:36,240
and to do that, you need some big souls.

1616
00:52:36,240 --> 00:52:38,160
Oh, cool. Thanks. Nice one.

1617
00:52:38,160 --> 00:52:39,120
So you do that.

1618
00:52:39,120 --> 00:52:40,400
Along the way, you find areas

1619
00:52:40,400 --> 00:52:43,680
and bosses strangely evocative of the previous ones.

1620
00:52:43,680 --> 00:52:47,840
Nadjka is, shall we say, Quelaag-adjacent.

1621
00:52:47,840 --> 00:52:50,640
The gutter is very Blighttown-y, and so on.

1622
00:52:50,640 --> 00:52:51,760
There's a lot of parallels,

1623
00:52:51,760 --> 00:52:53,360
but it's never quite made clear

1624
00:52:53,360 --> 00:52:55,680
that you're explicitly in the same world as Lordran

1625
00:52:55,680 --> 00:52:57,760
or at least not the same places.

1626
00:52:57,760 --> 00:52:59,840
There's just a subtle thing in the back of your head

1627
00:52:59,840 --> 00:53:02,080
about how this all seems oddly familiar.

1628
00:53:02,080 --> 00:53:03,200
So you kill all the enemies,

1629
00:53:03,200 --> 00:53:05,280
and on the way, there are these occasional locked doors.

1630
00:53:05,280 --> 00:53:08,000
There's no explicit sense that you're missing any large areas.

1631
00:53:08,000 --> 00:53:09,760
All the paths terminate in dead ends

1632
00:53:09,760 --> 00:53:12,480
or weird shrines with the primal bonfires in them.

1633
00:53:12,480 --> 00:53:15,120
The game is pretty long just accounting for these four paths.

1634
00:53:15,120 --> 00:53:16,560
So when you go to Castle Drangleic,

1635
00:53:16,560 --> 00:53:18,560
you get the sense this really is the end game.

1636
00:53:18,560 --> 00:53:20,240
You progress all the way through the castle

1637
00:53:20,240 --> 00:53:21,280
to the shrine beneath,

1638
00:53:21,280 --> 00:53:23,040
and then through the Grave of Saints.

1639
00:53:23,040 --> 00:53:24,720
There's a real sense of build-up.

1640
00:53:24,720 --> 00:53:25,840
Then you fight Velstadt,

1641
00:53:25,840 --> 00:53:27,680
who's guarding the door to Vendrick.

1642
00:53:27,680 --> 00:53:28,720
After beating him,

1643
00:53:28,720 --> 00:53:31,440
you finally go to meet your presumably final opponent,

1644
00:53:31,440 --> 00:53:35,040
the same final opponents you fought in Demon's Souls and Dark Souls 1,

1645
00:53:35,040 --> 00:53:37,680
the corrupted king of the world you've been walking through.

1646
00:53:37,680 --> 00:53:40,080
But instead, this happens.

1647
00:54:01,520 --> 00:54:04,880
Vendrick is a shadow of the man talked about in the lore

1648
00:54:04,880 --> 00:54:06,560
and by the characters that remember him.

1649
00:54:06,560 --> 00:54:08,480
He, like the fate of the rest of the undead,

1650
00:54:08,480 --> 00:54:10,720
like the player's character will eventually become,

1651
00:54:10,720 --> 00:54:11,920
has lost his mind.

1652
00:54:11,920 --> 00:54:13,760
You don't have to fight Vendrick at all.

1653
00:54:13,760 --> 00:54:15,120
He's not your enemy.

1654
00:54:15,120 --> 00:54:18,160
He's just a man who lost his way and everything else with it.

1655
00:54:18,160 --> 00:54:20,800
It's hard to relate how touching this is.

1656
00:54:20,800 --> 00:54:22,880
The game genuinely feels like it was building

1657
00:54:22,880 --> 00:54:25,040
to the very final confrontation.

1658
00:54:25,040 --> 00:54:27,280
It's a game about a man who's lost his way,

1659
00:54:27,280 --> 00:54:29,120
and he's trying to find his way back.

1660
00:54:29,120 --> 00:54:31,600
It was building to the very final confrontation.

1661
00:54:31,600 --> 00:54:34,160
The room is built to have a dramatic passage down steps

1662
00:54:34,160 --> 00:54:35,600
similar to the lead-up to Gwyn,

1663
00:54:35,600 --> 00:54:38,240
and it's built so that the camera naturally passes through it

1664
00:54:38,240 --> 00:54:40,720
to reveal what Vendrick has become.

1665
00:54:40,720 --> 00:54:42,000
I feel bad for spoiling it

1666
00:54:42,000 --> 00:54:43,760
for people who haven't experienced the game yet,

1667
00:54:43,760 --> 00:54:46,640
but this moment is pivotal to what makes the story interesting.

1668
00:54:46,640 --> 00:54:48,960
You're built up for the traditional Souls game encounter

1669
00:54:48,960 --> 00:54:50,080
with a fallen king,

1670
00:54:50,080 --> 00:54:51,520
and instead you're faced with a thing

1671
00:54:51,520 --> 00:54:54,080
to whom it doesn't even occur to fight you anymore,

1672
00:54:54,080 --> 00:54:55,920
shambling around almost naked.

1673
00:54:55,920 --> 00:54:57,680
You just have to pick up the king's ring,

1674
00:54:57,680 --> 00:54:59,120
which unlocks the final areas

1675
00:54:59,120 --> 00:55:00,960
and allows you to head to Aldia's keep

1676
00:55:00,960 --> 00:55:02,560
and eventually meet the ancient dragon

1677
00:55:02,560 --> 00:55:04,480
who's also not interested in fighting you.

1678
00:55:04,480 --> 00:55:06,240
He gives you the Ashen Mist Heart,

1679
00:55:06,240 --> 00:55:08,560
which lets you journey into the memories of giants

1680
00:55:08,560 --> 00:55:10,400
from the old war Vendrick fought.

1681
00:55:10,400 --> 00:55:11,920
You get to see a lot of the damage

1682
00:55:11,920 --> 00:55:14,000
that you encounter in the main path happening.

1683
00:55:14,000 --> 00:55:15,120
It's really neat.

1684
00:55:15,120 --> 00:55:17,360
Killing the giant lord lets you face Nashandra,

1685
00:55:17,360 --> 00:55:19,280
Vendrick's queen, at the Throne of Want.

1686
00:55:19,280 --> 00:55:22,000
Killing her nets you precisely one ending.

1687
00:55:22,000 --> 00:55:23,360
Your character sits on the throne,

1688
00:55:23,360 --> 00:55:25,200
presumably having become the new king,

1689
00:55:25,200 --> 00:55:26,720
and then the credits play.

1690
00:55:26,720 --> 00:55:28,400
But instead of resetting the game,

1691
00:55:28,400 --> 00:55:29,600
it just carries on.

1692
00:55:29,600 --> 00:55:31,040
You're put back in the world.

1693
00:55:31,040 --> 00:55:33,040
The game deliberately undercuts its story.

1694
00:55:33,840 --> 00:55:34,340
You win,

1695
00:55:34,960 --> 00:55:36,080
but what do you win?

1696
00:55:36,720 --> 00:55:38,720
Kingship over a dying world?

1697
00:55:38,720 --> 00:55:40,320
The chance to sit in a chair?

1698
00:55:40,960 --> 00:55:42,160
Only one character in the game

1699
00:55:42,160 --> 00:55:44,320
even recognizes you as the new king,

1700
00:55:44,320 --> 00:55:46,640
Shal'Kuar, the seemingly immortal cat

1701
00:55:46,640 --> 00:55:48,400
who also knows most of the rest of the lore

1702
00:55:48,400 --> 00:55:49,680
about the other bosses.

1703
00:55:49,680 --> 00:55:50,480
If you want to,

1704
00:55:50,480 --> 00:55:52,880
you can use bonfire ascetics to refight old bosses

1705
00:55:52,880 --> 00:55:54,640
or refresh enemies if you exhaust them,

1706
00:55:54,640 --> 00:55:56,560
or you can completely kill all the NPCs

1707
00:55:56,560 --> 00:55:57,760
even the Emerald Herald.

1708
00:55:57,760 --> 00:55:59,360
You can make the world of Dark Souls 2

1709
00:55:59,360 --> 00:56:02,320
completely empty of people and monsters.

1710
00:56:02,320 --> 00:56:04,000
The only way to access New Game Plus

1711
00:56:04,000 --> 00:56:05,520
is to sit at a bonfire

1712
00:56:05,520 --> 00:56:08,000
and deliberately choose to start it all over again.

1713
00:56:08,000 --> 00:56:09,120
I like these choices

1714
00:56:09,120 --> 00:56:10,960
because they hammer home the hopelessness

1715
00:56:10,960 --> 00:56:13,120
of the Dark Souls story that was there in one,

1716
00:56:13,120 --> 00:56:14,480
but undercut by the fact

1717
00:56:14,480 --> 00:56:15,760
no matter what ending you got,

1718
00:56:15,760 --> 00:56:17,520
you just started at the beginning again.

1719
00:56:17,520 --> 00:56:19,680
Dark Souls 2 forces you to contemplate

1720
00:56:19,680 --> 00:56:21,120
how little you've really achieved

1721
00:56:21,120 --> 00:56:22,320
with all these deaths,

1722
00:56:22,320 --> 00:56:24,080
and then forces you to decide

1723
00:56:24,080 --> 00:56:25,920
when it's time to do it all again.

1724
00:56:25,920 --> 00:56:28,720
Ultimately, Dark Souls 2 is about cycles.

1725
00:56:28,720 --> 00:56:30,400
The story is deliberately evocative

1726
00:56:30,400 --> 00:56:31,600
of the previous game,

1727
00:56:31,600 --> 00:56:33,600
exploring the empire of a king who fell,

1728
00:56:33,600 --> 00:56:34,880
but with an explicit focus

1729
00:56:34,880 --> 00:56:37,040
on how this has all happened before,

1730
00:56:37,040 --> 00:56:38,880
and not just coincidentally.

1731
00:56:38,880 --> 00:56:41,440
Perhaps it's something we're doomed to keep doing.

1732
00:56:41,440 --> 00:56:42,000
Humanity,

1733
00:56:42,000 --> 00:56:44,720
perhaps unable to ever fully escape its own nature,

1734
00:56:44,720 --> 00:56:47,200
is repeating its mistakes over and over.

1735
00:56:47,200 --> 00:56:49,280
For a game with so much architecture and character

1736
00:56:49,280 --> 00:56:50,720
in so many of its designs,

1737
00:56:50,720 --> 00:56:53,200
the best piece of imagery is the simplest one,

1738
00:56:53,200 --> 00:56:55,120
the symbol of the dark sign.

1739
00:56:55,120 --> 00:56:56,800
It's a loop, a circle,

1740
00:56:56,800 --> 00:56:58,800
reflecting the way the undead return to life

1741
00:56:58,800 --> 00:56:59,840
no matter what,

1742
00:56:59,840 --> 00:57:02,160
continuing even after they lose their minds.

1743
00:57:02,160 --> 00:57:04,960
Humanity itself is trapped in this loop.

1744
00:57:04,960 --> 00:57:06,960
The story is much more for the player

1745
00:57:06,960 --> 00:57:08,080
than in the previous game.

1746
00:57:08,080 --> 00:57:09,760
It's a story in which the player is expected

1747
00:57:09,760 --> 00:57:11,200
to contemplate their own actions

1748
00:57:11,200 --> 00:57:12,480
instead of those of others,

1749
00:57:12,480 --> 00:57:14,080
and recognize that the problem here

1750
00:57:14,080 --> 00:57:16,240
isn't the mistakes of the king or his people,

1751
00:57:16,240 --> 00:57:18,480
but that people as a whole were unable to escape

1752
00:57:18,480 --> 00:57:20,720
the mistakes that happened in Dark Souls 1.

1753
00:57:20,720 --> 00:57:22,640
But what's even better is how it makes sure to tell you

1754
00:57:22,640 --> 00:57:24,080
this isn't just one repeat.

1755
00:57:24,080 --> 00:57:26,080
No, the story of Dark Souls 1 has happened

1756
00:57:26,080 --> 00:57:27,760
maybe countless times,

1757
00:57:27,760 --> 00:57:30,960
so many you don't know and will never fully comprehend it.

1758
00:57:30,960 --> 00:57:32,800
In a prison cell in the Lost Bastille

1759
00:57:32,800 --> 00:57:34,240
is a man made of stone.

1760
00:57:34,240 --> 00:57:36,080
If you unfreeze him, he refers to himself

1761
00:57:36,080 --> 00:57:37,920
as Straid of Olaphis.

1762
00:57:37,920 --> 00:57:40,640
Olaphis was a kingdom where Drangleic now stands,

1763
00:57:40,640 --> 00:57:42,400
untold generations ago,

1764
00:57:42,400 --> 00:57:45,120
so long ago that no one but Straid

1765
00:57:45,120 --> 00:57:46,880
and the descriptions of spells and items

1766
00:57:46,880 --> 00:57:49,040
invented by him or belonging to him

1767
00:57:49,040 --> 00:57:50,160
even mention it.

1768
00:57:50,160 --> 00:57:52,400
In Dark Souls 1, all the various areas and people

1769
00:57:52,400 --> 00:57:53,680
and their stories and what happened

1770
00:57:53,680 --> 00:57:56,000
can be pieced together quite meticulously.

1771
00:57:56,000 --> 00:57:57,440
You can, with enough work,

1772
00:57:57,440 --> 00:58:00,240
put together a complete universe out of the facts.

1773
00:58:00,240 --> 00:58:03,440
In Dark Souls 2, an entire civilization

1774
00:58:03,440 --> 00:58:05,120
can be so utterly lost

1775
00:58:05,120 --> 00:58:07,840
that only one man even knows its name.

1776
00:58:07,840 --> 00:58:09,840
Who knows how many empires rose and fell

1777
00:58:09,840 --> 00:58:11,280
between Olaphis and Drangleic

1778
00:58:11,280 --> 00:58:13,200
or Lordran and Drangleic,

1779
00:58:13,200 --> 00:58:15,600
but pieces of them lie scattered everywhere,

1780
00:58:15,600 --> 00:58:17,520
decayed, colossal wrecks,

1781
00:58:17,520 --> 00:58:19,280
each with their own rise to power

1782
00:58:19,280 --> 00:58:20,480
and their own mad kings

1783
00:58:20,480 --> 00:58:22,800
and their own undead curse rending them apart.

1784
00:58:22,800 --> 00:58:25,040
The Forest of Fallen Giants is Vendrick's doing,

1785
00:58:25,040 --> 00:58:26,240
but Earthen Peak?

1786
00:58:26,240 --> 00:58:27,440
The Old Iron Keep?

1787
00:58:27,440 --> 00:58:29,840
These places rose and fell on their own terms.

1788
00:58:29,840 --> 00:58:31,680
The DLC, which we'll get to later,

1789
00:58:31,680 --> 00:58:33,840
each covers its own completely separate tale

1790
00:58:33,840 --> 00:58:35,360
of a kingdom that rose and fell

1791
00:58:35,360 --> 00:58:36,800
in roughly the same area.

1792
00:58:36,800 --> 00:58:37,920
What's compelling about this

1793
00:58:37,920 --> 00:58:39,120
is that it's more bizarre,

1794
00:58:39,120 --> 00:58:40,240
more unexplained,

1795
00:58:40,240 --> 00:58:41,680
and more human.

1796
00:58:41,680 --> 00:58:43,680
People in the Souls universe are victims

1797
00:58:43,680 --> 00:58:45,920
of a history they might never be able to learn.

1798
00:58:45,920 --> 00:58:48,240
The story is about being lost

1799
00:58:48,240 --> 00:58:50,720
in a confusing maze you can never fully understand,

1800
00:58:50,720 --> 00:58:52,720
a feeling strengthened by the nightmarish

1801
00:58:52,880 --> 00:58:54,480
of the actual physical world.

1802
00:58:54,480 --> 00:58:56,640
Quelaag alone was simply a sad story

1803
00:58:56,640 --> 00:58:58,560
about a woman transformed into a demon

1804
00:58:58,560 --> 00:59:00,480
by an attempt to create more life,

1805
00:59:00,480 --> 00:59:02,000
but now she's contextualized

1806
00:59:02,000 --> 00:59:04,080
as a victim of a far deeper problem

1807
00:59:04,080 --> 00:59:06,080
that mankind is having trouble escaping,

1808
00:59:06,080 --> 00:59:07,120
because no matter what,

1809
00:59:07,120 --> 00:59:09,600
it seems to keep happening over and over.

1810
00:59:09,600 --> 00:59:11,600
Something really cool and kind of subtle

1811
00:59:11,600 --> 00:59:13,760
is hidden in the basement of Majula.

1812
00:59:13,760 --> 00:59:15,280
Down, hidden in the dirt,

1813
00:59:15,280 --> 00:59:17,200
so small not many people notice,

1814
00:59:17,200 --> 00:59:18,880
is a small, fractured piece

1815
00:59:18,880 --> 00:59:20,800
of the Lordvessel from the first game.

1816
00:59:20,800 --> 00:59:21,920
This is the best expression

1817
00:59:21,920 --> 00:59:24,320
of what Dark Souls 2 is doing with its story.

1818
00:59:24,320 --> 00:59:25,680
It's interested in telling a story

1819
00:59:25,680 --> 00:59:27,920
about being unable to fully piece together

1820
00:59:27,920 --> 00:59:28,880
what's happening,

1821
00:59:28,880 --> 00:59:30,400
as the character loses their minds

1822
00:59:30,400 --> 00:59:32,880
in a doomed world of destroyed statues.

1823
00:59:32,880 --> 00:59:34,000
Your character doesn't even know

1824
00:59:34,000 --> 00:59:35,280
what a Lordvessel is.

1825
00:59:35,280 --> 00:59:36,640
To them, this is nothing,

1826
00:59:36,640 --> 00:59:38,240
just a thing lying in the dust.

1827
00:59:38,240 --> 00:59:40,080
It also represents the developers' attempts

1828
00:59:40,080 --> 00:59:41,840
to do their own thing and move on

1829
00:59:41,840 --> 00:59:44,160
by reducing an iconic part of the previous game

1830
00:59:44,160 --> 00:59:46,080
to a piece of rubble in a basement.

1831
00:59:46,080 --> 00:59:47,920
For me, the weakest parts of the previous games

1832
00:59:47,920 --> 00:59:49,840
is when I got handed a whole heap of names,

1833
00:59:49,840 --> 00:59:51,280
roles, and backstory.

1834
00:59:51,280 --> 00:59:52,400
Demon's Souls did this, too,

1835
00:59:52,400 --> 00:59:53,680
by just listing a bunch of people

1836
00:59:53,680 --> 00:59:54,880
who went into the fog.

1837
00:59:54,880 --> 00:59:56,080
I could just find those people

1838
00:59:56,080 --> 00:59:57,280
and learn about them manually,

1839
00:59:57,280 --> 00:59:58,640
but instead, the first games open

1840
00:59:58,640 --> 01:00:00,240
with a needless role call

1841
01:00:00,240 --> 01:00:02,160
and a story about a fight with dragons

1842
01:00:02,160 --> 01:00:03,760
that doesn't really tell me anything.

1843
01:00:03,760 --> 01:00:05,360
The guys I'm going to kill

